# migrated from tests/cases/rederive.chat (gen346, hermetic + isolated)
[mock hermetic]
!set PARROT0_BASE=
!set PARROT0_SESSION=
!set PARROT0_WORLD_FACTS=0
!set PARROT0_LANG=en
!reset

[test rederive]
# gen103 (L16): self-correction that RE-DERIVES. The engine already resolves
# rules at query time, so a retracted premise silently changes a conclusion.
# This generation makes the agent VOLUNTEER that downstream effect: when a
# correction flips a conclusion it previously stated, it says so unprompted.

> every man is a mortal
< Learned rule: mortal(X) :- man(X).
> socrates is a man
< Learned: man(socrates).
# The agent states (and remembers) a derived conclusion.
> is socrates a mortal?
< Yes.
# Correcting the premise retracts man(socrates); the agent re-derives the
# conclusion and announces the consequence in the SAME turn — joined-up reasoning.
> socrates is not a man
< Learned: not man(socrates). Then socrates is no longer a mortal.

# It also volunteers a NEWLY-enabled conclusion. Ask first (records "No"), then
# supply the missing premise: the derived class now holds, and it says so.
> every bird is a flyer
< Learned rule: flyer(X) :- bird(X).
> is tweety a flyer?
< No.
> tweety is a bird
< Learned: bird(tweety). Now tweety is a flyer after all.

# No spurious note: an unrelated assertion that does not change the remembered
# conclusion stays silent.
> plato is a man
< Learned: man(plato).
